The Two-Pointer Mastery Notes (Java)
📌 Foundational Checklist for Interviews
Space Complexity: Almost all two-pointer problems expect $O(1)$ auxiliary space. If you are creating new arrays or lists unnecessarily, it’s an interview red flag.
Primitive Types: When running additions or computations on array values (e.g., 3Sum, 4Sum), look out for Integer Overflow. Cast your operations to long.
Array Bounds: Always verify if arrays can be empty or have a length of 1 at the beginning of your method execution.

Pattern 1: Opposite Ends (Collision Course)
1. The Interview Triggers
*. The input array is sorted (or can be sorted without disrupting the required result indexes).
*. Finding pairs, triplets, or combinations matching a target value.
*. Operations processing elements from the outside moving inward (e.g., Reversals, Palindromes).

2. Core Mechanics
Two pointers are placed at opposite boundaries (left = 0 and right = array.length - 1). They move inward dynamically toward one another based on conditional checks until they meet or cross paths.

3. Production Java Blueprint
public int[] oppositeEndsTemplate(int[] nums, int target) {
    // 1. Handle base/edge cases
    if (nums == null || nums.length < 2) return new int[]{-1, -1};
    
    int left = 0;
    int right = nums.length - 1;
    
    // 2. Loop condition: Pointers must not cross
    while (left < right) {
        // Prevent overflow by casting to long if elements can be large
        long currentSum = (long) nums[left] + nums[right];
        
        if (currentSum == target) {
            return new int[]{left, right}; // Found target
        } else if (currentSum < target) {
            left++; // Sum is too small, move to a larger value
        } else {
            right--; // Sum is too large, move to a smaller value
        }
    }
    return new int[]{-1, -1};
}

4. Corner Cases & Interview Pitfalls
Duplicates Handling: In problems returning multiple combinations (like 3Sum), you must bypass matching elements sequentially to avoid duplicate sub-arrays:
while (left < right && nums[left] == nums[left + 1]) left++;
while (left < right && nums[right] == nums[right - 1]) right--;

5. Essential Interview Questions
Easy: LeetCode 167 - Two Sum II (Input Array Is Sorted), LeetCode 125 - Valid Palindrome
Medium: LeetCode 15 - 3Sum, LeetCode 11 - Container With Most Water
Hard: LeetCode 42 - Trapping Rain Water
